{{For|the mathematical term|Continuant (mathematics)}}
In [[phonetics]], a '''continuant''' is a [[speech sound]] [[manner of articulation|produced]] without a complete closure in the [[oral cavity]], namely [[fricative]]s, [[approximant]]s and [[vowel]]s.<ref>"continuant" in Bussamann, ''Routledge dictionary of language and linguistics'', 1996</ref> Approximants and vowels are sometimes called "frictionless continuants".<ref>"approximant" in Crystal, ''A dictionary of linguistics and phonetics'', 6th ed, 2008</ref> Continuants contrast with [[occlusive]]s, such as [[Stop consonant|stops]], [[Affricate consonant|affricates]] and [[Nasal consonant|nasals]].
Compare [[sonorant]] (resonant), which includes vowels, approximants and [[Nasal consonant|nasals]] but not fricatives, and contrasts with [[obstruent]].
Whether [[Lateral consonant|laterals]], [[Flap consonant|taps/flaps]], or [[Trill consonant|trills]] are continuant is not conclusive.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hayes|first=Bruce|authorlink=Bruce Hayes (linguist)|year=2009|title=Introductory Phonology|publisher=Blackwell|page=78|isbn=978-1-4051-8411-3}}</ref>
