{{Infobox book | name = Time Slave | title_orig = | translator = | image = File:TimeSlave.jpg | caption = First edition | author = [[John Norman]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = Gino D'Achille | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = | genre = [[historical fiction]], [[soft science fiction|science fiction]] | publisher = [[DAW Books]] | pub_date = 1975 | english_pub_date = | media_type = Print ([[paperback]]) | pages = 380 | isbn = 978-0-7592-9778-4 | oclc = 1942479 | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Time Slave''''' is a 1975 hybrid of [[historical fiction]] and [[soft science fiction|science fiction]] by [[John Norman]]. In this book, Norman presents his personal theories of human [[evolution]], exemplified by the case of a modern woman sent back in time twenty thousand years or more; he mourns the loss of human evolutionary fitness and distortion of "[[nature|natural]]" [[society|social relations]] which in his view occurred when [[farming]] spread and farmers squeezed hunter/gatherers to the ecological margins. ''Time Slave'' features Norman's social philosophy of male-dominance (as also in his ''[[Gor]]'' series), and expresses an unexplained connection between female sexual subordination and the speeding up of the development of space travel.
